## ğŸ§  What is Eastâ€“West Traffic?

**Definition:**  
Eastâ€“West traffic refers to **internal traffic flowing between workloads inside a cloud environment**, such as:
- VM to VM  
- Pod to Pod  
- Service to Service  

This traffic never leaves the cloud and often never touches the internet.

Opposite:
- **Northâ€“South traffic** â†’ User â†” Cloud  

---

## ğŸ¯ Why Eastâ€“West Traffic Matters

Reality in modern clouds:

- 80â€“90% of traffic is Eastâ€“West  
- Lateral movement happens here  
- Data exfiltration starts here  
- Zero-trust failures show here  

Classic mistake:
> â€œInternal traffic is trustedâ€

That assumption is how breaches spread.

---

## ğŸ§± Core Components of Eastâ€“West Inspection

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Micro-Segmentation

Workloads are segmented at:
- VM level  
- Pod level  
- Identity level  

Policies define:

Service A â†’ Service B (Allowed) Service A â†’ Database (Denied)

No flat internal networks.

---

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Inline Inspection Points

Inspection happens **inside the cloud fabric**, not at perimeter firewalls.

Common inspection points:
- Hypervisor networking layer  
- Kernel fast path (eBPF / XDP)  
- Virtual switches  
- Service mesh sidecars  

This ensures:
Every packet is inspected.  
Not just ingress traffic.

---

### 3ï¸âƒ£ Identity-Aware Policies

Rules are based on:
- Service identity  
- Workload labels  
- Certificates  
- SPIFFE / SPIRE identities  

Not IP addresses.

IPs change.  
Identities donâ€™t.

---

### 4ï¸âƒ£ Layer 7 Awareness

Modern inspection goes beyond ports.

It understands:
- HTTP methods  
- API paths  
- gRPC calls  
- Database queries  

Example:

Service A â†’ GET /health (Allowed) Service A â†’ POST /admin (Denied)

This is application-aware security.

---

## ğŸŒ How Eastâ€“West Traffic Flow Works

1. Service A sends request  
2. Traffic hits local enforcement point  
3. Identity is verified  
4. Policy is evaluated  
5. Traffic allowed or dropped  
6. Logs and metrics recorded  

This happens **per request**, not per session.

---

## ğŸ—ï¸ Where Inspection Happens (Architectures)

### Host-Based (Most Common)
- eBPF programs  
- Kernel filters  
- Virtual NIC enforcement  

### Sidecar-Based
- Service mesh proxies  
- Envoy sidecars  
- Full L7 inspection  

### Fabric-Based
- Virtual switches  
- SDN enforcement  
- Hardware offload  

Each has tradeoffs in:
- Latency  
- Visibility  
- Complexity  

---

## ğŸ” Eastâ€“West vs Northâ€“South Security

| Aspect | Eastâ€“West | Northâ€“South |
|-----|-----------|-------------|
| Traffic volume | Very high | Lower |
| Visibility | Low by default | High |
| Threats | Lateral movement | External attacks |
| Controls | Micro-segmentation | Perimeter firewalls |

Most breaches move sideways, not inward.

---

## ğŸ” Security Advantages

- Stops lateral movement  
- Limits blast radius  
- Enforces zero trust  
- Detects insider threats  
- Provides deep visibility  

Eastâ€“West inspection turns internal networks into hostile territory â€” intentionally.

